Here's a complete implementation:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

// Configure Kestrel and form size limits
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 10 * 1024 * 1024);
builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o =>
{
    o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 10 * 1024 * 1024;
});

var app = builder.Build();

// Ensure uploads folder exists
var uploadsPath = Path.Combine(app.Environment.ContentRootPath, "uploads");
Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsPath);

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    // Validate content type
    string[] allowed = ["image/jpeg", "image/png"];
    if (!allowed.Contains(file.ContentType))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are accepted.");

    // Validate size (defense in depth — Kestrel also enforces this)
    if (file.Length > 10 * 1024 * 1024)
        return Results.BadRequest("File must be 10 MB or smaller.");

    // Generate a safe, unique filename preserving extension
    var ext = Path.GetExtension(file.FileName).ToLowerInvariant();
    if (ext is not ".jpg" and not ".jpeg" and not ".png")
        return Results.BadRequest("Only .jpg, .jpeg, and .png extensions are allowed.");

    var savedName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{ext}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsPath, savedName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName = savedName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()   // required for API file uploads without a form token
.DisableRequestSizeLimit() // optional: remove if you want Kestrel's limit to remain
.WithName("UploadImage");
```

**Key points:**

- **Three layers of validation** — content type, file size, and extension — so a renamed `.exe` won't sneak through on content type alone.
- **`Guid` filenames** prevent path traversal and collisions.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** is needed per-endpoint because your pipeline has `UseAntiforgery()`; without it, API clients without a form antiforgery token will get a 400. If your clients *do* send the token, remove that call.
- Remove `.DisableRequestSizeLimit()` if you want the 10 MB Kestrel cap to stay active (the in-handler check still applies either way).
